column46: One of the (many) problems of Christian nationalism is being taught that humans have dominion over the earth in a way that means humans can use and abuse without any consequences. This interpretation was never intended in the Scriptures, and I believe humans are largely in denial about the consequences of our actions and greed. And Christians are no exception, and in some cases, the worst abusers.

column46: I appreciate the social/personal benefits conferred by pocket parks and the ecological benefits conferred by larger parks.  However, pocket parks are so small that they rarely function as contiguous habitat for anything more than non-winged insects or microorganisms.  They offer benefits, they are not a good substitute for other ecological practices that can take place on larger pieces of land (including suburban lawns).

column46: Caring for pocket parks, setting aside the resources to care for them, and encouraging community ownership of park health and order as very important factors in policy development. Pocket parks can’t fulfill environmental, social and real estate benefit goals if they are not well cared for and seen as a positive asset. It can be especially demoralizing to a community to start with an ambitious development but experience decline because maintenance and the sustainability of the project was neglected.
